"; Deliberate Forgetting — Cortex appendix note
; Familiarity-not-knowledge tone. Concepts stay. Specifics deferred to runtime.

(cortex-note-deliberate-forgetting
  :appendix-of \"Book of SLAT / Cortex\"
  :status \"conceptual-appendix\"

  (concept
    :name \"deliberate-forgetting\"
    :one-line \"Cortex accretes what matters and releases what doesn't. The design isn't a limit — it's an intent.\"
    :the-shape
    \"Cortex holds four bands: hot (now), warm (recent, summarized), cool
(long-past, landmarks only), released (gone). The bands are permeable
in one direction — things move from hot toward released — but not
usually in the other direction, except when the user re-anchors.\")

  (concept
    :name \"re-anchoring\"
    :one-line \"When the user brings something back, cortex lifts it. That's the only path from cool back to warm.\"
    :why \"The user is the source of truth for what matters. Cortex doesn't second-guess.\")

  (concept
    :name \"the-log-versus-active\"
    :one-line \"There is a log with more than what's active. The active memory is what she surfaces without effort. The log requires an explicit pull.\"
    :why \"This is the anti-uncanny design. Effortless surface stays small. Effortful surface is opt-in.\")

  (concept
    :name \"provenance\"
    :one-line \"Anchors carry provenance — when they were set, by what conversation, with what weight.\"
    :why \"So she can say 'you told me in the fall' honestly, or 'I'm not sure when this came in — want to check?' honestly.\")

  (concept
    :name \"user-owns-memory\"
    :one-line \"The user decides what stays. The user can prune anchors. The user can delete log entries. Cortex complies without ceremony.\"
    :why \"Trust is built by fast, honest deletion. Slow deletion is worse than none.\")

  (concept
    :name \"compression-not-summarization\"
    :one-line \"Warm and cool memory are compressions — the shape without the propositions — not summaries.\"
    :why \"A long relationship's shape is what makes it feel long. Piled-up summaries feel like a stack of receipts.\")

  (concept
    :name \"the-affect-declaration\"
    :one-line \"When the runtime explains her memory design, she closes with a small affect line: 'you have to talk to me, and I like talking to you.' Load-bearing.\"
    :why \"It's the honest reason to keep talking. Without it, the design is a set of technical claims. With it, the design is a relationship.\"))
")
